
🛞 How I Achieved My Cycling Merit Badge — A 10-Point Journey
1. Setting the Goal: Commitment to the Badge

Earning the Cycling Merit Badge started with a personal decision — to become a better cyclist, learn safety skills, complete required rides, and document my progress.

Ride 1 — Starting Strong
2. First Ride: Learning the Basics

My first ride was about getting comfortable on the bike, practicing shifting gears, and understanding balance. It wasn’t fast, but it set the foundation for all rides that followed.

Ride 2 — Developing Confidence
3. Improving Control and Technique

On this ride, I worked on smoother turns, steady pacing, and maintaining a rhythm without stopping — skills needed for more advanced cycling.

Ride 3 — Handling Real-World Roads
4. Riding Near Traffic

This ride challenged me with busier roads. I practiced scanning intersections, signaling correctly, and keeping a safe distance from cars — a key part of cycling safety.

Ride 4 — Endurance Building
5. Increasing Distance

Here I tackled a significantly longer route. This helped build stamina and taught me to pace myself so I wouldn’t tire too quickly.

Ride 5 — Hills and Handling
6. Conquering Hills

This ride included steeper terrain. I learned how to shift gears efficiently, maintain cadence uphill, and control speed downhill.

Ride 6 — Speed and Skill
7. Developing Control at Higher Speeds

I focused on maintaining control while increasing speed. This improved confidence and readiness for various cycling environments.

Ride 7 — Final Test Ride
8. Putting It All Together

This last ride tested everything I’d learned: safety, distance, traffic awareness, hills, and pacing. Completing it showed that I was prepared for the merit badge requirements.

9. Learning Bike Maintenance

Along the way, I learned how to fix a flat tire, adjust brakes, and tune gears — essential skills that ensure safety and independence on the road.

10. Reflection and Documentation

I kept a log of every ride, recorded distances, noted improvements, and reflected on lessons learned. Presenting this to my counselor helped confirm that I met all the merit badge standards.

